The paper deals with the computational complexity of electoral control in a specific voting system, which falls under the category of computational social choice (cs.GT). The use of external agents to tamper with the outcome of an election is a common topic in artificial intelligence (cs.AI) and the analysis of algorithms for parameterized complexity is a key aspect of theoretical computer science (cs.DS). The paper also involves the manipulation of data structures and algorithms for voting, which falls under the category of machine learning (cs.LG) and data mining (cs.DM).
